message.content:
Testimony 2 states that at the scene a memo was found with the killer’s name “Maya” scrawled in blood. However, Evidence 4—the item called “Maya’s Memo”—is actually a recorded conversation on Maya’s cell phone rather than the blood-written note described by Gumshoe. This discrepancy shows that what Gumshoe claims to have found contradicts the documented evidence of Maya’s recorded memo.

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 2}

April’s fourth statement describes the murder weapon as “that clock” – a reference to the clock-like statue known as “The Thinker.” Yet one of the physical pieces of evidence (the department store Receipt, Evidence 3) shows a purchase for a glass light stand, and its shattered remains (Evidence 2) were found at the scene. This suggests an object made of glass was involved rather than a clock, contradicting her identification of the weapon. 

{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 4}

The evidence titled “May Testimony” (Evidence 9) states that “The victim dodged an attack then ran to the right, but she was caught and struck,” whereas White’s testimony (Testimony 8) asserts “The victim ran to the left, and you gave chase!” These two accounts contradict each other regarding the direction in which the victim fled. 

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 8}

There is a clear contradiction regarding the victim’s direction when fleeing. Evidence 9 (May Testimony) states that "the victim dodged an attack then ran to the right," while Testimony 1 from White says that "when you assaulted the girl, she first ran to the left." This inconsistency about her initial direction is the pair that contradict each other.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 1}

White stated in Testimony 1 that he observed a light stand lying on the floor. However, Evidence 2 reveals that what was found were merely the broken remains (glass shards) of a light stand. This is a contradiction: if the light stand had been intact enough to be noticed as a whole object on the floor, it wouldn’t have been reduced to unrecognizable shards.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 1}

White testified in Testimony 3 that he saw the glass light stand when he entered the law offices; however, Evidence 8 (the Floor Plans) clearly shows that the stand is blocked from view from the office. This contradiction indicates that White’s statement about seeing the light stand is at odds with the spatial layout shown by the evidence.

{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 3}

Evidence 5 shows a photo from 2:00 PM of Steel Samurai (Powers) walking while dragging one leg—a sign of difficulty or injury. In contrast, Oldbag’s Testimony 7 confidently claims she saw Powers at that exact time, striding toward the studio. His apparent impaired gait in the photo contradicts the impression given by Oldbag that he was fully in control and heading purposefully to his destination.

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 7}

Oldbag insists that if anyone besides Will Powers had passed by en route to the studio, she would have seen them (Testimony 3). Yet the security camera’s view was obstructed—Evidence 11 “Mr. Monkey’s Head” was blocking the path between 2:15 PM and 4:00 PM. This means that even if someone did go by, Oldbag might not have seen them. Thus her claim “If they had, I would have seen them!” is called into question by the fact that the view was blocked during a critical time.

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 3}

Cody claims in his final statement (Testimony 8) that he didn’t have his camera with him at the crucial moment – saying “If I had my camera with me, that woulda been the time for a shot.” Yet, the evidence labeled as “Cody's Camera” (Evidence 15) clearly indicates that he always carries his new digital camera. This contradiction between his claim of not having his camera on hand and the fact that he is known for always carrying it is puzzling.

{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 8}

Cody states in Testimony 3 that his camera’s lens “wouldn't open in time” and he missed taking any picture. However, Evidence 5—the Powers' Photo—shows a photograph taken at the precise time (Oct 15, 2:00 PM) at the gate. This contradiction between Cody claiming he failed to capture any image and the existence of a photo taken at that moment suggests a discrepancy between his testimony and the evidence.

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 5 claims that Vasquez and Sal ate t‑bone steaks on the table in front of the trailer, but at the scene the table had only an empty plate—with no sign of any meal having been served or eaten. This clear discrepancy between what Vasquez says and what the scene shows is a contradiction. 

{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 5}

The photographic evidence (Evidence 5) shows Will Powers at the gate around 2:00 PM, with him noticeably dragging one leg. This directly contradicts Vasquez’s statement in Testimony 1 where she claimed that Powers was absent from the scene. The photo proves that he was indeed present, opposing her claim that everyone was there except him.

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 1}

Lotta’s testimony claims she clearly saw Mr. Edgeworth on the boat as the shooter. However, the Letter from the Safe (Evidence 20) instructs someone to “Get your revenge on Miles Edgeworth” – implying that Edgeworth was the target rather than the killer. These two pieces conflict because if Edgeworth had been on the boat operating the gun, there’d be no need to seek revenge against him.

{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 0}

Lotta claims in her testimony that the camera was set up to take pictures of a meteor shower (Testimony 3), yet the description on Lotta's Camera (Evidence 2) clearly states it is programmed to take a picture when a loud noise is detected. This is a contradiction between her stated purpose for the camera and its actual function.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

Evidence 10—the murder weapon—was fired three times, yet Butz’s testimony 5 states he only heard a single gunshot. This is a direct contradiction.

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 5}

Lotta's Deposition (Evidence 11) claims that two sounds like gunshots were heard just after midnight on 12/25, while Butz’s testimony (Testimony 3) insists he only heard one gunshot. This inconsistency in the number of shots constitutes a contradiction between the evidence and the testimony.

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 3}

The contradiction lies between Lotta's Deposition, which states that two sounds like gunshots were heard just after midnight on 12/25 (Evidence 11), and Edgeworth’s testimony stating that there was only a single gunshot before a scream (Testimony 5). This discrepancy in the number of gunshots is a clear counterpoint between the evidence and testimony.

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 5}

Detective Gumshoe points at the costume, insisting, “As you can see, it's covered in blood,” yet the evidence description of Maya's Costume specifies that it only has "blood splatters" and remains otherwise clean except for a bullet hole in the sleeve. This exaggeration contradicts the actual state of the costume as described.

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 3 states that the victim's shot missed due to their close range. However, Evidence 8 (Dr. Grey's Autopsy Report) clearly indicates that after being stabbed, the victim was shot in the forehead at point-blank range—with gunpowder residue corroborating the shot. This contradicts the testimony about the victim's missed shot, suggesting instead that the fatal shot was accurate and deadly. 

{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 3}

The contradiction is between Evidence 11, which describes Maya Fey’s costume as blood-splattered with a bullet hole in the sleeve, and Testimony 4, where Ini states that "her costume looked totally, like, normal." This discrepancy suggests a conflict regarding the condition of Maya’s costume at the time of the murder.

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 4}

Evidence 6 (Newspaper Clipping 2) indicates that Ini's older sister, Mimi Miney, died in a car accident one year ago. However, in Testimony 3, Ini recalls taking her sister to the Channeling Chamber, suggesting that she was still alive at that time. This contradiction makes evidence 6 and testimony 3 inconsistent with each other.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 3}

The contradiction lies between Newspaper Clipping 2 (Evidence 6) and Ini’s statement about who was driving. In the clipping, Ini is quoted as saying, "I was like, really tired and I dropped off to sleep," which implies that she was the one driving (and then fell asleep), yet in her own testimony she states, "…the night of the accident, my sis was totally tired while she was driving" (Testimony 2). This discrepancy between Ini’s quoted account in the newspaper and her verbal testimony creates a clear contradiction.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 0 implies that Ini was still in the process of getting her driver's license ("really close to getting my license"), yet Evidence 18 shows a completed driver's license photo that is being kept as a prized possession. This creates a contradiction because if the license photo is from an already issued driver's license, then Ini wouldn’t merely be close to obtaining it.

{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 0}

Trilo repeatedly claimed that the engagement ring he planned to give to Regina (and never did, keeping it in his pocket) was still with him. However, Evidence 10—the cheap ring with the eerie sparkle—is known to be in Phoenix Wright’s possession, which contradicts Trilo’s claim that he still had it in his pocket.

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 5}

Trilo’s account of greeting Max and receiving no acknowledgment (Testimony 3) doesn’t match a scenario where Max shows up as scheduled for a pre‐arranged meeting. The Note (Evidence 16) clearly instructs that the meeting should occur at 10:00 PM at the lodging house plaza. If Max had come according to that instruction, one would expect at least a proper greeting upon arrival. Instead, Trilo’s testimony implies an absent or dismissive behavior that contradicts the planned meeting indicated on the Note.

{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 3}

Moe’s fourth testimony states, “His cloak was fluttering in the wind, so I couldn't really see what he was carrying,” implying uncertainty about what Max had with him. Yet, the silk hat—a distinctive accessory and one of Max’s “uppity symbols”—was clearly found at the crime scene (Evidence 3). In other words, if Moe really couldn’t see what Max was carrying, it’s odd that such a conspicuous item as the silk hat was present and later recovered, directly contradicting his claim of uncertainty. 

{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 4}

Moe insists in his testimony that no white roses were present that night (Testimony 0). However, the Max G. Promo Poster (Evidence 4) clearly displays white roses as one of Max’s three famous symbols. This pair is contradictory.

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 0}

Acro insists (in Testimony 3) that his lower‐body was so injured he couldn’t produce the force needed to look out the window and locate the victim’s head. However, the Crime Photo (Evidence 2) clearly shows footprints and the victim’s body positioned on the box—details that indicate the head’s location was visible or could have been deduced by someone at that scene. This undermines Acro’s claim of being completely unable to see where the head was.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 5 makes the case sound like the murder was premeditated via the knife—that is, the defendant bought the knife to commit the crime. But Juan’s Autopsy Report (Evidence 14) tells us that the victim was first strangled with a scarf and then stabbed. This discrepancy in the murder method places the emphasis on two very different manners of killing. If the knife were truly the premeditated murder weapon, one would expect it to be solely implicated in the cause of death. Instead, the autopsy report shows that strangulation played a crucial role, contradicting Gumshoe’s assertion in Testimony 5.

{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 5}

Oldbag testified that the man leaving Juan’s room was wearing "his flashy racing jacket," which she attributed to Matt Engarde. However, Lotta’s Photo (Evidence 17) shows a person in samurai garb standing outside the door. Since Engarde’s public persona is that of the Nickel Samurai, one would expect him to be seen in proper costume—not in a racing jacket. This discrepancy between the witness’s testimony (Testimony 5) and the photographic evidence (Evidence 17) represents a contradiction.

{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 5}

The Nickel Samurai costume is described as a fully covering outfit complete with masks and gloves. Witness Oldbag's Testimony 4 claims that “he must’ve worn that Nickel Samurai costume when he was stabbing poor Juan.” However, if Engarde had been wearing a fully gloved costume, his fingerprints wouldn’t have been left on the knife murder weapon. In contrast, Evidence 15 (the Knife) bears Engarde’s fingerprints. This contradiction suggests that either Oldbag’s assertion is mistaken or the evidence was misinterpreted.

{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 4}

Andrews claimed in her testimony (Testimony 5) that she knocked the flower vase over, implying that she made physical contact near the victim’s guitar case. However, Evidence 7 shows that the guitar case bears only Juan Corrida's fingerprints. If Andrews had been responsible for toppling the vase onto the case, her fingerprints would likely have been present there, which contradicts her statement.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 5}

Andrews testified that she opened the guitar case (see testimony 1), yet the guitar case (evidence 7) bears only Corrida's fingerprints. This discrepancy indicates a contradiction—if Andrews had indeed opened the case, her fingerprints should be present. 

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 8 (the wine glass) shows that Andrews’ fingerprints are on an item found next to the victim, even though in her testimony (for example, in Testimony 0 where she claims she immediately saw the crime scene and deduced Matt was the killer) she presents herself as an impartial witness whose observations prove Matt’s guilt. If she were simply a detached witness pointing a finger at Matt, finding her fingerprints at the scene undermines her objectivity and suggests she was physically present and involved. This pair—the wine glass’s physical evidence versus her claim of purely observing the scene—stands out as contradictory.

{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 0}

Andrews claims that she went to pour the victim some juice because she assumed he had just fainted (Testimony 4). However, the wine glass found at the scene (Evidence 8) is full of tomato juice and shows no sign that any juice was consumed—an odd detail if she had been pouring him a drink. This discrepancy between her claim and the physical state of the glass is the contradiction.

{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 1 states that Powers saw the bellboy coming out of Corrida’s room, yet Evidence 17 (Lotta’s Photo) clearly shows a person in samurai garb outside the door in the hallway rather than someone fitting the bellboy’s description. This discrepancy directly contradicts Powers’ claim, as the photographic evidence does not support the presence of a bellboy at the scene.

{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 1}

Testimony 5 claims that the knife (and a button) was created and planted to mislead the investigation. However, Evidence 15 shows a knife with Engarde’s fingerprints, suggesting it was not an intentionally planted decoy by Andrews but rather handled by Engarde. This inconsistency between the claimed planted evidence and the physical fingerprint evidence contradicts de Killer’s testimony.

{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 5}

Testimony 4 is problematic because de Killer claims “When I saw the name at the end of the letter, I thought my client to be a man.” However, all other accounts and evidence (for example, the bear figurine—as detailed in Evidence 25, which only Juan Corrida and Andrews know how to open) clearly indicate that his client was Adrian Andrews, a woman. This contradiction between what de Killer claims to have thought (a male client) and the evidence linking the request to Andrews forms a direct conflict.

{"evidence": 25, "testimony": 4}

Evidence 20 (Ron’s Testimony) reveals that from Mask☆DeMasque’s second heist onward, his thefts were being carried out under the direction of blackmail letters—implying that he wasn’t choosing his targets based on his own taste. This contradicts Detective Gumshoe’s Testimony 3, where he claims that Mask☆DeMasque’s pattern is to always go after only the most precious art pieces. If he were simply following orders, his selection wouldn’t necessarily reflect a personal predilection for “precious art,” undermining Gumshoe’s assertion of a consistent M.O.

{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 3}

Atmey’s testimony (Testimony 2) describes being struck as he began to turn—in effect suggesting a frontal blow—whereas Evidence 6 specifically notes that Mask☆DeMasque knocked him out with a blow to the back of his head. This discrepancy in the location (and implied nature) of the blow is a clear contradiction between the testimony and the physical evidence.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

The testimony from Atmey (Testimony 5) states: "I put my back to the wall to fight, but the thief's blow landed upon my third eye," implying that the blow struck him on the forehead area. Meanwhile, Evidence 6 (Shichishito) indicates that Mask☆DeMasque knocked Atmey out with a blow to the back of his head. These two accounts contradict each other about where Atmey was struck. 
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 5}

Ron claims in Testimony 5 that his broach was simply snagged on a door handle and torn off. However, Evidence 14 (DeMasque's Broach) was found concealed in the shadow of Ami Fey's statue—a location and circumstance that do not coincide with his explanation. This discrepancy between his stated account and the location where the broach was discovered directly contradicts his testimony.

{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 5}

Atmey claims he never laid eyes on the urn until the day of the crime, yet Mask DeMasque’s calling card (Evidence 5) shows he referenced the urn—specifically noting its “speckled” appearance—before the heist took place. This indicates that DeMasque must have seen the urn well in advance, which directly contradicts Atmey’s claim of first seeing it on the day of the crime.

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 2}

Evidence 5, DeMasque's Calling Card, implicates Mask DeMasque as the criminal behind the night's crimes, yet in Testimony 5 the witness asserts that Ron DeLite was the one who killed Kane Bullard. This pair contradicts each other by pointing to a different perpetrator for the murder.

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 5}

Evidence 2—the Magazine Clipping—claims that the defense attorney was "trounced" and his client found guilty, suggesting a messy, unfavorable outcome. In testimony 3, however, Gumshoe maintains that after identifying the victim quickly, the investigation went smoothly. These two items don’t add up: how could the case be handled so effortlessly when the published report shows a devastating defeat in court? This contradiction between the smooth investigative narrative and the disastrous trial outcome is our chosen pair.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

One potential contradiction lies between Evidence 3 (“Sports Paper”) and Testimony 0. The sports paper is described as having been doodled on and left by the victim, implying that it was handled by the victim during—or before—the incident. However, in Testimony 0, Kudo states, “The young man was reading the sports paper,” which implies that someone else was handling it at the time, not the victim who left his mark. This discrepancy raises questions about who actually interacted with the sports paper at the time of the incident.

{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 0}

The coffee cup (Evidence 13) is marked only with the victim’s and Maggey’s fingerprints, yet Testimony 4 claims that a “little fidget” (someone else) picked it up and sipped from it. This discrepancy indicates that if someone else had handled the cup as described, their fingerprints should have been present, contradicting the forensic evidence.

{"evidence": 13, "testimony": 4}

The crime photo (Evidence 12) clearly shows that there is an intact vase on each table, yet in Testimony 2, Kudo claims that a clumsy individual upset the vase by knocking it over. This contradiction between physical evidence and testimony makes a strong case for a discrepancy in the accounts.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 2}

Armstrong claimed that a mirror was placed in the middle of the restaurant (Testimony 0), but the crime photo (Evidence 12) clearly shows that the dining tables were separated by a folding screen—not a mirror. This inconsistency in the description of the restaurant’s dividing element is a direct contradiction.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 0}

Armstrong asserts in testimony 6 that “there was no time for a phony to do la acting,” yet Evidence 7 – the Scooter – is described as having been ridden by “my phony.” This implies that someone acting as a phony was indeed present, directly conflicting with Armstrong’s statement.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 6}

The contradiction arises from Tigre's claim in Testimony 2 where he states that he "never saw that kid before" (referring to the victim, Glen Elg), while Evidence 20, "Glen's Calendar," specifically notes a meeting with "The Tiger" on the day of the incident. If Glen had set a meeting with The Tiger, it inherently contradicts Tigre's claim of never having seen him. 

{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 2}

Tigre claims in Testimony 0 that he never met Glen Elg, yet Evidence 20 (Glen's Calendar) clearly shows a note “Meet with The Tiger” on the day of the incident. This contradiction suggests that despite his denial, a meeting with Glen was scheduled. 

{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 0}

Tigre claims he barely stuck around – saying that after opening the door he left quickly because the place wasn’t “hot” (Testimony 3). Yet a small bottle found in the kitchen – whose fingerprints belong to him – clearly suggests he entered further than he admits and even handled items behind the counter (Evidence 6). This contradiction indicates his account of a brief, surface‐level observation is at odds with the physical evidence linking him to a deeper presence in the restaurant.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 3}

Evidence 13 – the Coffee Cup – shows that the victim’s drink contained lethal potassium cyanide, while in Testimony 3 Tigre claims he was about to assault the victim physically ("flatten the guy") when the victim started screaming. This physical confrontation narrative does not match a poisoning death. In other words, if Tigre’s account of a physical altercation were true, the cause of death wouldn’t be a cyanide poisoning as indicated by the Coffee Cup.

{"evidence": 13, "testimony": 3}

Bikini’s testimony states that Iris came to the Inner Temple after dinner, while Iris’s own testimony (Evidence 12) claims she rang the lights out bell at 10 PM and then stayed in her room. This is a clear contradiction regarding Iris’s location that night.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 3}

Bikini's Testimony 3 states, "Iris didn't have her hood on," which directly contradicts Evidence 6 that shows Iris's Hood—a garment known to be worn by her at all times. This inconsistency suggests that either Bikini’s observation or the assumption about the hood’s constant use is flawed.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 3}

Bikini’s second testimony claims she saw a blade being drawn out at the moment of the crime. However, evidence shows that the weapon—which appears to be the bloody sword, Shichishito—had the victim’s blood and suspect’s fingerprints, yet it is confirmed not to be the murder weapon. In other words, her description of witnessing the extraction of a blade contradicts the physical evidence that the obvious bloody sword was not the one used to kill Elise.

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 2}

Bikini’s testimony (Testimony 2) claims she saw multiple tracks clearly indicating that a snowmobile was used. However, the Tracks Photo (Evidence 14) shows only a single track leading from the Main Gate to Dusky Bridge. This discrepancy between the “multiple tracks” described in her statement and the “one track” captured in the evidence contradicts her account.

{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 2}

Butz claimed that when he looked out of his window he saw the Dusky Bridge burning (Testimony 2), yet the weather data (Evidence 7) tells us that lightning struck the bridge at 10:45 PM—meaning any fire would have started later than when Butz implies he saw it. This timing discrepancy between his observation and the factual weather timeline is contradictory.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 2}

Butz claims he saw Iris flying with her white hood (Testimony 2), yet Iris herself stated she rang the lights out bell and then stayed in her room until the murder was discovered (Evidence 12). This directly contradicts Butz’s account of her being seen flying since if she were in her room, she could not have been seen in flight.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 2}

Iris's testimony number 3 claims that Elise tossed aside her staff and pulled a dagger from inside her robe. However, Evidence 9—the Victim's Staff—clearly shows that Elise’s staff (which contained a hidden sword) was indeed the murder weapon. This contradiction between what Iris observed and what the physical evidence shows is significant.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 3}

Iris’s testimony #3 states that "Mystic Maya stabbed Mystic Elise!" However, the evidence provided by the Victim's Staff (Evidence #9) shows that the actual murder weapon—a hidden sword within Elise’s own staff bearing her fingerprints—was involved in the killing. This implies that Elise's own item, rather than a weapon wielded by Maya, was used to commit the murder, thereby contradicting Iris’s account.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 3}

The weather report (Evidence 7) shows that snow was falling until about 10:50 PM on the night of the crime, while Iris's testimony (Testimony 6) claims that the snow had already stopped by the time the murder took place. This inconsistency between the weather evidence and her account indicates a direct contradiction.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 6}

Maya claims in Testimony 4 that she saw “a man behind my attacker by the light of the stone lantern,” implying that the lantern was lit and providing sufficient light. However, Evidence 20 clearly states that the stone lantern was not lit on the night of the crime, contradicting her testimony.

{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 4}

Maya testified that “The torches were lit… And the body was gone” (Testimony 3), implying that the garden was deliberately illuminated by someone during or after the incident. Yet, the physical evidence at the crime scene—the Stone Lantern found in the Inner Temple garden (Evidence 20)—was reported as “not lit the night of the crime.” This clear contrast, between Maya’s observation of lit torches and the unlit lantern, contradicts the description of the scene.

{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 3}

Larry's sketch (Evidence 15) shows a silhouette gliding over the burning bridge that night, suggesting someone was already active on site during the crime. This evidence contradicts Maya’s testimony (Testimony 3) that Mr. Godot arrived at the Inner Temple for the first time the next day, implying he wasn’t seen around the bridge when the incident occurred. 

{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 4 states that the victim was shot in the forehead, “square in the forehead,” yet Evidence 11 – Meraktis's Autopsy Report – clearly establishes that the bullet struck the victim’s right temple. These two accounts contradict one another regarding the location of the fatal shot.

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 4}

The eyewitness account says the killer used a pistol—Stickler clearly recalls “the killer raised his pistol” (Testimony 0)—while at the crime scene a knife (Evidence 10) bearing Wocky’s prints was recovered. This pair directly contradicts each other since the victim was killed by a bullet (as shown in the autopsy) and the testimony pinpointed a gun, not a knife. 

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 0}

The sign on the noodle stand is described by the evidence as reading "ELDOON," yet the witness Stickler claims in testimony 4 that the sign said "NOODLE." This contradiction between the evidence and testimony is significant.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 4}

Alita claims in testimony 4 that she had no reason to go to the clinic for a “half‐year‐old chart,” implying she wasn’t involved in routine clinic business. Yet, evidence 18—the clinic’s chart signed by her—shows that she was indeed present and responsible for updating or handling patient records, a clear indication that she was at the clinic for matters related to this (albeit old) chart. This discrepancy between her statement and the physical record contradicts her account.

{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 4, where Brushel asserts “Those spasms... That was definitely death by poison,” contradicts Evidence 15, which is Magnifi's Autopsy Report stating that his cause of death was a single gunshot wound to the head.

{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 4}

Brushel’s second testimony states that the envelope he observed was yellow, yet the envelope actually recovered—the one in the victim’s desk (Evidence 9)—is described as a red envelope. This discrepancy creates a clear contradiction between the witness’s description and the physical evidence.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 2}

Lamiroir stated in Testimony 4 that she saw nothing and that Mr. LeTouse’s body was “behind a wall.” However, the Diagram (Evidence 10) detailing the crime scene shows that the victim’s body was positioned in a room—not hidden behind a wall—with bullet holes on the wall near the door visible from the entrance. This discrepancy between her claim and the physical layout creates a clear contradiction.

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 4}

Evidence 15 (the Igniter) is linked to triggering a device in Klavier Gavin’s guitar, whose igniter (Evidence 17) burned down during the concert. This points toward a culprit who handled a musical instrument—a person like Gavin—who is not blind. However, Testimony 5 states, “From the state of the crime scene, I conclude the shooter was blind,” thereby directly contradicting the implication from Evidence 15. 

{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 5}

Testimony 3 claims that Mayor Tenma aggressively attacked his victim, impaling him with a weapon (suggesting that the mayor was the one doing the striking). However, Evidence 7—the Fox and Demon Statue—shows that the statue (used as a weapon) bore the mayor’s blood, implying that the victim struck back with the statue and injured the mayor instead. This contradiction pits the narrative of an aggressive mayor against physical evidence showing he was on the receiving end of a blow.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 3}

Explanation: Testimony 4 from Fulbright claims that Mayor Tenma killed the sleeping alderman, which places him as the one committing the murder. However, Evidence 7 – the Fox and Demon Statue – is described as “the weapon used to bludgeon the mayor” and even has the mayor's blood on it. This clearly contradicts the testimony because it implies that the mayor was instead a victim of an assault rather than the perpetrator of the crime.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 4}

Filch’s TV Listings (Evidence 13) reveal that a wrestling program was on at 3 PM—a show he mentioned watching. However, in his testimony (Testimony 0) he insists he was on guard duty in the foyer at that exact time. Being on guard duty in the foyer would make it unlikely for him to have been watching the program, so this pair of evidence and testimony contradict each other.

{"evidence": 13, "testimony": 0}

Filch insists in Testimony 4 that there wasn’t any sign of Tenma Taro in the foyer, yet Evidence 12—Jinxie’s eyewitness account—reports that the demon was seen in the hallway and fled toward the foyer. This contradiction suggests that one of them is mistaken about the demon’s presence in that area.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 4}

Filch’s testimony 2 claims that Tenma Taro possessed (and used) a big staff when entering the foyer, yet at the scene the murder weapon turns out to be the Fox and Demon Statue (Evidence 7)—a heavy, wrapped statue with the mayor’s blood on it—clearly suggesting a different object was used. This pair contradicts each other regarding the weapon in question.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 2}

Evidence 2—the Tenma Taro Warding Charm—is said to have been given to L'Belle by Jinxie as he headed to the crime scene. However, in Testimony 1, L'Belle claims that when Jinxie learned of her father’s crime, she fled without even noticing him. She couldn’t have given him the charm if she never paid attention to him. This direct contradiction between the interaction implied by Evidence 2 and the account in Testimony 1 stands out.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 19 – the Hand Cream bearing the “Je suis L’Belle” logo – was found inside the Forbidden Chamber. In his testimony (number 5), L’Belle insisted that “The Forbidden Chamber was shut tight until the mayor opened it,” which implies he had not entered that room. The fact that an item clearly associated with him ended up inside the Forbidden Chamber contradicts his claim of never being there before the mayor opened it.

{"evidence": 19, "testimony": 5}

L'Belle’s testimony paints the existence of Tenma Taro as a demonic curse that seals the village’s fate—implying a supernatural, malevolent presence behind the statue.
